. French Wine is the first synthetic history of wine in France: from Etruscan, Greek, and Roman imports and the adoption of wine by beer-drinking Gauls to its present status within the global marketplace. Rod Phillips places the history of grape growing and winemaking in each of the country’s major regions within broad historical and cultural contexts. Examining a range of influences on the wine industry, wine trade, and wine itself, the book explores religion, economics, politics, revolution, and war, as well as climate and vine diseases. French Wine is the essential reference on French wine for collectors, consumers, sommeliers, and industry professionals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aWine and wine makingxSocial aspectszFrancexHistory. 0aWine and wine makingzFrancexHistory. 0aWinexSocial aspectszFrancexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  a17th century winemaking.  a18th century french winemaking.  aalgeria.  aalgerian wine.  aappellations.  abordeaux.  achampagne.  afrench regions.  afrench vineyards.  afrench wine in the middle ages.  afrench wine regions.  afrench wine.  ahistory of french wine.  ahistory of wine.  ahistory of winemaking in france.  ahistory of winemaking.  amodern winemaking in france.  anew french wine regions.  apinard.  asommelier reference.  asommelier.  aviticulture.  awine and wine making.  awine reference book.  awine regions in france.  awine.  awinemaking.  awines of france.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052028523140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096077040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520960770423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520960770/original  a978-3-11-06675